{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.04,0.06,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52170"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4968"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4606"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52170"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to an emergency department with acute onset confusion. She reports dysuria for two days with noticeable blood in her urine. Her temperature is 38.6 degrees, systolic blood pressure is 85mmHg despite fluid resuscitation with 3 litres of crystalloid, pulse rate is 122/min and oxygen saturations SpO2 97% on room air. Her examination is significant for warm and flushed peripheries with an undetectable JVP when examined at 45 degrees. Her ECG shows a sinus tachycardia. She has a history of unprovoked DVT 4 years ago, recurrent UTIs and has a family history of a cardiac arrhythmia she doesn\u0027t know the name of.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic shock","Hypovolemic shock","Cardiogenic shock","Cystitis","Obstructive shock"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E secondary to urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECirculatory shock is a syndrome caused by decreased perfusion of the organs. In distributive shock, there is decrease systemic vascular resistance, manifested clinically as warm peripheries with a bounding pulse during the early phases. Later in the course of distributive shock there is compensatory vasoconstriction with tissue hypo-perfusion and the skin may become cold and clammy.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterized by decreased cardiac output from cardiac pump failure primarily, which presents with cold peripheries, elevated capillary refill times and usually venous congestion. While she has a possible family history of arrythmia her fever and dysuria point more towards a urosepsis picture.  In \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E, decreased cardiac output is caused by some sort of obstruction in the circulatory system preventing adequate cardiac pump function (e.g. a pericardial tamponade or large pulmonary embolism). These patients also present with cold and clammy skin and usually venous congestion. Despite her history of DVT her fever and sinus tachycardia, combined with normal oxygen saturation indicate sepsis as a more likely cause of her shock.  \u003Cstrong\u003EHypovolemic \u003C/strong\u003Eshock also decreases cardiac output by decreasing preload, causing cold peripheries but without the venous congestion often seen in cardiogenic or obstructive shock.  Bleeding in urine is common in UTIs due to the effect on local membranes, and is highly unlikely to cause bleeding sufficient to induce shock.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warm and hyperaemic skin in a patient with hypotension is suggestive of early distributive shock.","Simple examination of the skin in a shocked patient can yield useful information about the aetiology."],"references":["Vincent J-L, De Backer D. Circulatory Shock. New England Journal of Medicine. 2013;369(18):1726-34."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37498"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T17:57:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T17:59:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4968"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52170"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi